# GNU Affero General Public License (AGPL) v3 — Summary

## Overview

The **GNU Affero General Public License v3** (AGPLv3), published on **19 November 2007** by the **Free Software Foundation**, is a strong copyleft license specifically designed for software used over networks. It ensures that users interacting with modified software over a network have access to the corresponding source code.

> "The GNU Affero General Public License is designed specifically to ensure that, in such cases, the modified source code becomes available to the community."

---

## Key Definitions

- **"The Program"**: Any copyrightable work licensed under this License.
- **"Covered work"**: Either the unmodified Program or a work based on it.
- **"Modify"**: To adapt or copy part/all of a work in a way requiring copyright permission (excluding exact copies).
- **"Propagate"**: Any action that would make you liable for copyright infringement (e.g., copying, distribution, public availability).
- **"Convey"**: Propagation enabling others to make or receive copies (mere network interaction without transfer is *not* conveying).
- **"Corresponding Source"**: All source code needed to build, install, run, and modify the work—excluding System Libraries and general-purpose tools.

---

## Core Permissions & Conditions

### ✅ Basic Permissions (Section 2)
- You may **make, run, and propagate** covered works without restriction, as long as your license remains in force.
- You may convey works to others **for the sole purpose** of having them modify it exclusively for you, under your direction.

### 📤 Conveying Modified Source (Section 5)
When distributing modified versions, you **must**:
- Include **prominent notices** stating the work was modified and the date.
- Release under **this License + any Section 7 additional terms**.
- License the **entire work as a whole** to all recipients.
- Ensure **interactive interfaces display Appropriate Legal Notices** (if applicable).

### 📦 Conveying Object Code (Section 6)
You must provide **machine-readable Corresponding Source** via one of:
- Physical media with source included,
- Written offer (valid ≥3 years) for source at no more than cost of distribution,
- Free network access to source (e.g., via download link),
- Peer-to-peer transmission with clear source availability info.

> For **User Products** (consumer goods), you must also provide **Installation Information** to enable reinstallation of modified versions.

---

## Special Provisions

### 🔒 Anti-Circumvention (Section 3)
You **waive** any legal right to block users from circumventing technological measures when exercising rights under this License.

### ⚖️ Patent Licensing (Section 11)
- Each contributor grants a **non-exclusive, royalty-free patent license** for essential patent claims.
- If you **knowingly rely** on a patent license and don't provide source, you must either:
  - Make source publicly available,
  - Relinquish your patent benefit, or
  - Extend the patent license to downstream users.

### 🌐 Network Use Requirement (Section 13)
> "If you modify the Program, your modified version must prominently offer all users interacting with it remotely... an opportunity to receive the Corresponding Source... at no charge."

This is the **key differentiator** from GPLv3: **network interaction triggers source disclosure**.

### 🔗 Compatibility with GPLv3 (Section 13)
You may **combine** AGPLv3-covered works with GPLv3-licensed works. The AGPL part remains under AGPLv3; the combined work as a whole can be conveyed under AGPLv3.

---

## Additional Terms (Section 7)

You may add **permissive or non-permissive** terms, including:
- Disclaiming warranty differently,
- Requiring attribution,
- Prohibiting misrepresentation of origin,
- Limiting use of names/trademarks,
- Requiring indemnification.

⚠️ **"Further restrictions"** (e.g., fees, royalties) are **not allowed** and can be removed by recipients.

---

## Termination & Reinstatement (Section 8)

- **Violation** of the license **automatically terminates** your rights.
- Rights are **reinstated**:
  - **Provisionally**, if you stop violating,
  - **Permanently**, if the copyright holder doesn't notify you within 60 days of cessation, **or** if it's your first violation and you cure it within 30 days of notice.

---

## Warranty & Liability

### ❌ No Warranty (Section 15)
> "THERE IS NO WARRANTY FOR THE PROGRAM... THE ENTIRE RISK AS TO THE QUALITY AND PERFORMANCE OF THE PROGRAM IS WITH YOU."

### 🛑 Limitation of Liability (Section 16)
No copyright holder or modifier is liable for **any damages** (direct, indirect, incidental, consequential) unless required by law or agreed in writing.

---

